# Cursor rules: frontmatter (canonical for TLC)

Every **new or edited** rule file under `.cursor/rules/` should start with YAML frontmatter so Cursor can scope and prioritize the rule correctly.

## Required keys (use unless you have a deliberate exception)

| Key | Purpose |
| --- | --- |
| `description` | Short human-readable summary (shown in rule pickers / reviews). |
| `globs` | Array of path globs; rule applies when those paths are in scope. Use `["**/*"]` for workspace-wide behavior. |
| `alwaysApply` | `true` if the rule should be included without relying only on file hits; pair with `globs` per project needs. |

## Example (copy and edit)

```yaml
---
description: "One-line summary of what this rule enforces"
globs: ["**/*"]
alwaysApply: true
---
```

## Notes

- Prefer **one concern per file**; split long rules instead of one giant block.
- **Overlap on purpose:** `tlc-universal-response-format.mdc` is global (`**/*`); `tlc-universal-response-format-projects.mdc` repeats the same report shape for `projects/**` as defense-in-depth—do not delete one without an explicit decision.
- If a rule must stay **machine-local only**, add its path under `.gitignore` (this repo keeps `.cursor/rules/openmemory.mdc` ignored).
